# 11. Build calculation engines as pure functions

Every calculation engine should be pure:

```ts
function calculateLifeGap(
  inputs: LifeInputs,
  assumptions: LifeAssumptions
): LifeCalculationResult
```

No React state. No formatting. No JSX. No side effects.

Then separate:

```ts
function buildLifeViewModel(
  result: LifeCalculationResult
): LifeViewModel
```

This gives you cleaner testing, cleaner UI, and easier advisor review.

---

# 12. Make assumptions visible in the UI

The tool will be more trustworthy if the advisor can see the assumptions driving the numbers.

Each module should have an “Assumptions Used” area.

Example for Liability:

```text
Disposable income proxy: 65% of gross income
Garnishment rate: 25% of disposable earnings
Income growth: 3% annually
Umbrella block size: $1M
```

Example for Unemployment:

```text
Net income proxy: 65% of gross income
Minimum reserve: 3 months
Ideal reserve: 6 months
Reason: remaining income covers only 27% of expenses
```

This is critical because the tool is illustrative. Assumption transparency reduces compliance and trust issues.

---

# 13. Report architecture should come later

Do not prematurely build exports or advisor reports until the calculation layer is stable.

But architect now so future reports can consume:

```ts
CalculationResult
ViewModel
FormulaRegistry
DisclosureCopy
```

Then a PDF/report layer can simply render the same values the UI uses.

